%N A299900 Coordination sequence for "ftu" 3D tiling with respect to second type of node.
%C A299900 First 127 terms computed by _Davide M. Proserpio_ using ToposPro.
%C A299900 I have to say that I am not very confident about the conjectured g.f. below. We only have 128 terms, and the recurrence has 57 or so coefficients and 57 or so initial terms, and 114 is pretty close to 128. So not much of a safety margin. If the same g.f. still holds when we get 500 terms I will believe it. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 03 2021
%C A299900 From _Steven Kotlarz_, Jun 25 2026: (Start)
%C A299900 This empirically corroborates the conjectured generating function/recurrence above to the 500-term margin requested in the 2021 comment by _N. J. A. Sloane_. The submitted 501-term table supplies the requested margin. The terms were computed independently from the RCSR CGD description of the ftu net: expanding the Fm-3m symmetry gives a translation-labeled quotient graph with 288 vertices and 576 undirected edges, every vertex of degree 4. The same quotient graph gives A299898 from node type 1 (root vertex 0), agreeing with its existing b-file, and gives this sequence from node type 2 (root vertex 192). The first 128 A299900 terms agree with the existing b-file, and the extension through n = 500 agrees with the proposed rational generating function P(x)/Q(x).
%C A299900 The leading growth term in the conjectured formula is (11/7)*n^2. Although Q has quasi-polynomial period 1008, only the constant coefficient has full period 1008; the n^2 coefficient is constant and the n coefficient has period 12.
%C A299900 The g.f. denominator for A299898 is (1-x)^3*Phi(3,x)*Phi(7,x)*Phi(8,x)*Phi(9,x) (degree 21, quasi-period 504), which divides the degree-53 denominator of A299900 (quasi-period 1008). The quotient is Phi(3,x)*Phi(4,x)^2*Phi(6,x)*Phi(12,x)*Phi(16,x)*Phi(21,x). (End)
%H A299900 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A299900/b299900.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..500</a> (first 128 terms from Davide M. Proserpio)
%H A299900 V. A. Blatov, A. P. Shevchenko, and D. M. Proserpio, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1021/cg500498k">Applied Topological Analysis of Crystal Structures with the Program Package ToposPro</a>, Cryst. Growth Des. 2014, 14, 3576-3586.
%H A299900 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A299900/a299900.gp.txt">Standalone finite PARI/GP algebra check for the submitted terms, denominator, recurrence, and quasi-polynomial data</a>
